## Disposition record (revision 3)

- **Architecture — SUSTAINED.** Existing artifacts remain canonical facts. The ledger is reframed as the canonical append-only observation journal. Events bind source-set, extractor-contract, schema-set, configuration, and semantic-boundary digests. Generations and individual events are hash-linked; corruption starts a successor without in-place repair. Head checkpoints live in the tracked private repository. Reports identify the consumed generation, checkpoint, source set, and extractor. Sections changed: §§1, 2.4–2.5, requirements 2 and 6–12, §§4.1–4.5, 4.9–4.10, 5–9.

- **Finding 1 — SUSTAINED, SCALED.** Dispatch capture is limited to one bounded nonblocking journald datagram using `sd_journal_sendv` or `/dev/log` with `MSG_DONTWAIT` semantics. There are no capture file writes, `fsync`, retries, acknowledgements, helpers, or Claude wrappers in dispatch. Post-hoc collection materializes journal records. Fault tests cover absent/blocked socket, full buffer, quota rejection, `EINTR`, short result, fd exhaustion, cancellation, serialization failure, and helper absence. Sections changed: §§1, requirements 4–5 and 17–20, §§4.7, 5, 6 (`P2-02`, `P2-03`), 7, 8.4, 9.

- **Finding 2 — SUSTAINED.** Event identity includes every contributing source plus extractor, schema, boundary, and configuration digests. Capture and disposition observations are one event per record; snapshot families have explicit supersession. Companion-artifact and contract-drift fixtures are required. Sections changed: requirements 9–12, §§4.2–4.6, 4.9, 6 (`P2-01`), 8.2–8.3.

- **Finding 3 — SUSTAINED.** Epoch is `post-phase-1` only through a captured harness-commit binding to the pinned implementation/schema/boundary set. Otherwise it is `unknown`. Trends and A/B reject unknown or mixed epochs mechanically. Sections changed: §§1–3, §§4.3, 4.6, 4.10, 4.15, 6 (`P2-01`, `P2-05`, `P2-08`), 7–8.

- **Finding 4 — SUSTAINED.** `P2-01` consumes a generated committed Phase 1 extractor contract containing function signatures, output schemas, complete enum/mapping tables, schema digests, generator digest, and exhaustive tests. Every run verifies it; unsupported values emit `measurement_error`. Sections changed: §§2.3–2.4, requirements 1 and 9, §§4.3–4.6, 6 (`P2-01`), 7–8.

- **Finding 5 — SUSTAINED.** Report data is base64-embedded in an inert element. Hard limits cover every input and aggregation layer. Non-UTF-8 Git paths are represented losslessly or fail explicitly. Disposition writes use `openat2`/dirfd containment. Links reject schemes and containment escapes. Hostile fixtures include `</script>`, `javascript:`, U+2028/U+2029, control characters, huge inputs/diffs, traversal, and non-UTF-8 filenames. Sections changed: requirements 24–25, §§4.6–4.10, 6 (`P2-04`, `P2-05`), 7–8.

- **Finding 6 — SUSTAINED.** No journal generation is repaired. Damage seals the original bytes and starts a hash-linked successor. Tracked checkpoints detect complete-line truncation. Crash validation covers every byte boundary, visible-write/`fsync` failure, truncation, mutation, and concurrent genesis. Sections changed: §§1, requirements 6–8, §§4.2, 4.4–4.5, 6 (`P2-01`), 7, 8.3, 9.

- **Finding 7 — SUSTAINED.** Golden worker and reviewer processes both reuse the existing D5 `codex-worker` boundary with empty HOME, scrubbed environment, no operator credentials/fds, no production mounts/remotes, and existing worker network policy. Bundle validation proves exact ref/object closure. Production-side-effect canaries fail closed before invocation. Sections changed: requirements 28–29, §§4.11, 5, 6 (`P2-06`), 7, 8.5.

- **Finding 8 — SUSTAINED, SCALED.** The dataset uses a Merkle digest covering manifests, specs, modes, fixture closure, oracles, hidden checks, schemas, scorer, isolation profile, and ordered tasks. Manifests contain real rubric criteria. An operator-owned tracked holdout registry defines two task IDs and rotation epoch; routine mode rejects them. Task bodies live in the private repository. Public-task inspectability is recorded as a residual risk. Sections changed: requirements 27, 30, and 33, §§4.11–4.13, 4.15, 6 (`P2-06`–`P2-09`), residual risks, 8.5.

- **Finding 9 — SUSTAINED.** Rubric assertion kinds are enumerated and bound to trusted hidden oracle, attestation, diff, integrity, and terminal-truth sources. Reviewer catch requires a structured affected-path/rule/outcome match or blinded adjudication; keywords cannot earn points. Sections changed: requirements 30–31, §4.12, 6 (`P2-06`, `P2-07`), 7–8.

- **Finding 10 — SUSTAINED.** Reviewer-value experiments freeze one worker artifact/evidence digest and fork only after it. Arm manifests record intervention, evaluator digest, post-review outcome, and shared probe/fixture/label digests. `eval/reviewer-value` and `eval/reviewer_value.py` are added to `P2-07` allowed paths with a direct-resolution/no-copy test. Sections changed: requirement 34, §§4.1, 4.14, 5, 6 (`P2-07`), 7–8.

- **Finding 11 — SUSTAINED.** Per-task n=2–3 reports raw paired differences and descriptive ranges, never confidence intervals. Aggregates use predeclared task→paired-repeat hierarchical resampling with fixed seed derivation, 10,000 draws, and complete-case rules. Results include `paired_n`, one-sided missing counts/reasons, and intent-to-treat failures. Percentage deltas are null for bounded/count/rate metrics and below declared thresholds. Scheduling is deterministic AB/BA. Trusted runner/scorer/oracle/isolation are outside both commits. Full causal configurations are hashed and compared. Arithmetic is corrected to 33 pairs/66 full runs, with routine totals derived from recorded holdout IDs. Sections changed: requirements 35–42, §§4.9, 4.15, 6 (`P2-08`, `P2-09`), 7–8.

- **Finding 12 — SUSTAINED.** `P2-03` now precedes `P2-02`; no wrapper integration remains. Raw capture schemas are owned by `P2-01`. The matrix runner writes finalized artifacts only, and only the collector appends the journal. `measure bootstrap` and `measure doctor` define fresh-clone behavior. `as_of` derives from the journal head unless supplied. Canonical JSON fixes key, array, numeric, and newline serialization. `generated_at` exists only in noncanonical HTML metadata. Sections changed: requirements 22–23, 36, and 43, §§4.1, 4.7, 4.10, 4.15, 6 ordering and `P2-01`/`P2-03`/`P2-02`/`P2-05`/`P2-08`, 7–9.
